post_text:
At this time, the decision to reopen schools is with Governor Murphy. He does not intend to assess the reopening of schools until at least April 17, 2020, at the earliest.

Knowing that the school closure will be much more protracted than originally anticipated, we are responding to the need to provide a more direct instructional approach including moving forward with new content. I am working diligently with the administrative staff to develop schedules and instructional plans that are developmentally appropriate to the varying grade-levels and that address the specific needs of our special education population. We will share the parameters of the plan with faculty, parents, and students as soon as is possible.

Sincerely,
Diane DiGiuseppe

Kinnelon Schools is donating the following to the Morris County Office of Emergency Management. We provided 7360 medical-grade gloves, 500 poly gloves, 950 surgical masks, 20 N95 masks, and 304 Safety goggles and glasses.
Thanks to the Alan Bresett and our custodial crew who rounded it all up and dropped it at the Board office yesterday and today. Teamwork to keep our healthcare workers on the front lines safe and healthy!

UPDATE: Mr. Bresett came through with 12,000 more medical grade gloves! We also were able to donate several cases of alcohol prep pads! Thank you Mr. Bresett!!

post_text: In light of the growing number of COVID-19 cases in NJ, with the first presumptive case identified in Morris County this afternoon, we have decided that in the best interest of the students and greater Kinnelon community, Kinnelon Schools will be closed as of Monday, March 16, 2020, through the end of Spring break, April 10, 2020. It is my hope that schools will re-open Monday, April 13, 2020, however, I will reevaluate the situation throughout the closure period and continue to communicate with families via School Messenger email broadcasts and social media. Flexible Instructional Days will be in effect. Check the district website www.kinnelonpublicschools.org for more information.

post_text:
How many 9th-grade students would give up a Saturday to have a Leap Year lunch with their former first-grade teacher?

Most of them when it is former Kiel School teacher Annika Levitt!

To teach her (2011-2012) first-grade students the tough concept of Leap Year, she suggested they get back together every Leap Year for pizza and "leapfrog" cupcakes. Amazed that her students tower over her, Annika was pleasantly surprised by the response. The pictures show the students in grade 1, the first reunion in grade 4, and then again this past Saturday as 9th-grade students.

Thank you, Annika, for showing how Kinnelon educators care about their students! We miss you!

post_text: Originally established in 1885 in recognition of President George Washington, the holiday became popularly known as Presidents' Day after it was moved as part of 1971’s Uniform Monday Holiday Act, an attempt to create more three-day weekends for the nation’s workers. Presidents' Day is now popularly viewed as a day to celebrate all U.S. presidents, past and present.

post_text: During the less than 13 years of Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr.’s leadership of the modern American Civil Rights Movement, from December 1955 until April 4, 1968, African Americans achieved more genuine progress toward racial equality in America than the previous 350 years had produced. Dr. King is widely regarded as America’s pre-eminent advocate of nonviolence and one of the greatest nonviolent leaders in history. The Kinnelon Schools community honors the life, dream, and work of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.

Mrs. Castelluber and Mrs. Greco's English 3 classes participated in a mock Canterbury Tales feast to culminate the prologue of The Canterbury Tales. In the prologue, Geoffrey Chaucer's narrator proposes that each pilgrim tell two tales on their pilgrimage to Canterbury Cathedral and two tales on the way back to the Tabard Inn. The person / pilgrim with the best story wins a free dinner paid by the rest of the travelers. Students each wrote their own modernized pilgrim prologue poems, feasted during presentations, and voted on whose poem was the best. #kea #kinneloneducators #khscolts #kinneloncolts #canterburytales

post_text: Amazing Grace sung by KHS vocalists Alexa Giacoio, Julianna Marston, and Katie Nieto during a tribute to those lost during the attacks of September 11, 2001.
text: Amazing Grace sung by KHS vocalists Alexa Giacoio, Julianna Marston, and Katie Nieto during a tribute to those lost during the attacks of September 11, 2001.

post_text:
Today, Kinnelon High School Principal Gary Suda and the KHS administrative team, members if the KHS Student Council, KHS musicians Sam Bowers and Grace Goldberg, KHS vocalists Alexa Giacoio, Julianna Marston, and Katie Nieto, Superintendent Diane DiGiuseppe, Board of Education President Mr. DeAlessi, Kinnelon Police Chief John Schwartz, KHS Student Resource Officer Steve Caputo, members of the Kinnelon Police Department, Kinnelon Fire Department First Assistant Chief Stearn, Councilmen Yago, Russo, (Mayor) Sisco, and Charles of the Kinnelon Borough Council and members of the community remember those brave heroes who lost their lives during the September 11, 2001 attacks on the United States of America. We remember and honor those lost and thank the brave men and women of the Police, Fire, and Rescue of NY, NJ, Port Authority, Washington, D.C. and Shanksville, PA for their heroic attempts at rescue and the ultimate recovery efforts at the World Trade Center, the United States Pentagon and in a field at Shanksville, PA.

We will never forget.

post_text:
Music for Hope Suicide Awareness Concert.

Music For Hope (M4H) is a Concert for Suicide Awareness. During this event, there will be different youth artists performing, a poetry table along with information tables. In addition, there will be a speaker from the American Foundation of Suicide Prevention (AFSP) along with a suicide survivor sharing her story.

M4H is a nonprofit movement committed to using the Arts as a mechanism to promote awareness and information against suicide.

The event is Friday, May 17 @ Fusion Cafe 10 Jericho Rd. Butler beginning at 6:00pm- 9:30pm. All proceeds go to AFSP.

Kinnelon High School Ranked in the 90th percentile by the NJ Department of Education!

NJ Department of Education recently released its annual School Performance Reports. Based on statewide performance metrics, Kinnelon High School ranked #10 among all public high schools statewide (non-charter, non-magnet, non-technical, non-academy) and #4 among public high schools in Morris County, one of the most top achieving counties in the state. Congratulations to our students, faculty, staff, parents and the Kinnelon community for this special recognition as one of the best public high schools in New Jersey!

Mrs. Castro's Art Major 1 class produced beautiful work while learning about Indonesian headdresses. While the class collection will be available to view in Mr. Suda's weekly newsletter, there were standouts that Mrs. Castro submitted to Fresh Perspectives at the Morris Museum.

Fresh Perspectives is a exhibition that began in 1989 as an outlet for artistically-accomplished New Jersey high school students to express their curiosity and creativity. This year's Fresh Perspectives at the Morris Museum is Saturday, March 9, 2019 – Sunday, June 9, 2019. Congratulations to students Christina Avato and Nicole Van Niekerk (grade 12) and Miray Celikkol and Kelsey Thompson (grade 11) whose work was submitted to the exhbit.

Kiel School
December 6, 2018 at 9:52 PM ·

2nd grade teachers at Kiel School planned for a math flexible grouping day. Studies show that grouping students according to need helps to close the achievement gap. Students worked at various readiness levels exploring math fact families. Some students worked on building math fact families using manipulatives, others represented math fact families with pictures, while the rest represented math fact families at the symbolic level and generated "impostor facts" (facts that didn't belong with the fact family). The level of excitement was astounding and the kids all agreed that they had an awesome time and can't wait to do it again! 👍

On October 16, Student Assistance Counselor Danielle Wysocki and Kinnelon High School students placed 500 pinwheels across the front lawn of the school to spread awareness about the dangers of underage drinking.

The Pinwheel Project is designed to visually represent the 5,000 youth who die as a result of alcohol. Each pinwheel represents 10 deaths due to underage drinking,

Pictured are students Samuel Calabrese, Christiana Caprio, Tyler Daniels, Jason Rienzo, and Mitchell Donus.

post_text: School Safety Specialist, Vincent Shivas, along with School Resource Officer Russell Curving, Principal Michele Fisher, KHS English teacher Lisa Castelluber and her Humanities students Emily Kemp and Erin O’Mara present an original story to Mrs. Cook’s second-grade class. The story called OINK, written by KHS seniors Kemp and O’Mara explains school safety in a different way. The story, based on the Three Little Pigs, describes how the pigs are tested to keep the ‘big bad wolf’ put of their house or to flee to a safer place. Mr. Shivas, Mrs. Cook, and Mrs. Fisher debriefed after to make connections with school safety. The students enjoyed the story and came away with valuable understandings of how to react in a dangerous situation in the classroom or school environment. Thank you to all involved! We are sure the other classes will have as much fun learning about school safety.
